<laravel-extra-guidelines>
=== .ai/actions rules ===

# Actions

- Prefer reusable Action classes in `app/Actions`.
- Name actions by what they do, with no `Action` suffix required by the call site.
- Keep a single public `handle()` method per action.
- Inject dependencies through the constructor using promoted properties.
- Wrap multi-model writes in transactions.

=== .ai/data rules ===

# DTOs

- Prefer DTOs over loose arrays at application boundaries.
- Use readonly DTOs when the data should not change after construction.
- Keep DTOs explicit and fully typed.

=== .ai/quality rules ===

# Quality

- Push errors left with static analysis and strict CI rules.
- Prefer PHPStan, Rector, Pint, Oxlint, and Oxfmt at strict settings.
- Keep new code free from debug helpers and silent fallbacks.

=== .ai/php rules ===

# PHP

- Use `declare(strict_types=1);`.
- Prefer `final` classes by default.
- Prefer `readonly` objects when mutation is not required.
- Type every property, parameter, and return value.

=== .ai/laravel rules ===

# Laravel

- Keep controllers thin and move business logic into actions.
- Prefer explicit requests, DTOs, and focused services over large controllers.
- Favor eager loading, strict model behavior, and immutable dates where appropriate.

=== .ai/skills rules ===

# Skills

- If available, use `.ai/skills/actions.md` for action workflows.
- If available, use `.ai/skills/dto.md` for DTO workflows.
- If available, use `.ai/skills/enum.md` for enum workflows.
- If available, use `.ai/skills/crud.md` for CRUD workflows.
- If available, use `.ai/skills/quality.md` for verification and quality workflows.
</laravel-extra-guidelines>
